      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">Californium is a synthetic, transuranic element - an artificially prepared radioactive element. It belongs to the actinide series. Its most stable isotope is  </text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">251</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">Cf with a half-life of about 900 years. The properties of californium have not been fully established, due to the insufficient quantities of this element that could be isolated so far. The following californium compounds have been prepared successfully to date: californium(III) oxide  – C</text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">f</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">2</text>
      </subsup>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">O</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">3</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">, californium(III) chloride  – CfC</text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">l</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">3</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0"> and californium(IV) oxide – Cf</text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">O</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">2</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">. Californium is a hazardous element, due to its radioactivity and tendency to accumulate in bones. Californium was discovered in 1950 by the American researchers: </text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238"> Glenn T. Seaborg, Stanley G. Thompson, Kenneth Street and Albert Ghiorso, and named after the state of California.</text>
   </par>
